President Donald J. Trump issued a proclamation on July 25, 2018, in celebration of the 28th anniversary of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA). The ADA, signed into law by President George H.W. Bush on July 26, 1990, promotes equal access and rights for Americans with disabilities in various aspects of life, including employment, government services, public accommodations, commercial facilities, and public transportation. The proclamation reaffirms the commitment to further opportunities for all Americans with disabilities to live independent lives and acknowledges the contributions they make to society. The administration encourages research advancements, equal education, and employment opportunities for individuals with disabilities. The proclamation calls upon all Americans to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies and activities that celebrate the contributions of Americans with disabilities and renew the commitment to achieving freedom for all.